### History

Before the sleek, updated logo of the post-2010 era, the SCIAC, like all things, bore the marks of its past. The previous emblem, undoubtedly a product of its time, has since been relegated to the archives of historical design.

The genesis of the SCIAC was not an instantaneous creation but rather an evolution from earlier, more rudimentary athletic organizations. A direct forerunner, the Intercollegiate Football Association of Southern California, operated during the 1890s, a period when the very concept of organized collegiate sports was still finding its footing. This early association included institutions that would later become integral to the SCIAC, such as [Occidental College](/Occidental_College) and [Caltech](/California_Institute_of_Technology) (then known as Throop Polytechnic Institute). Its membership also featured institutions that would diverge onto different paths, like [USC](/USC_Trojans_football), [Chaffey College](/Chaffey_College), and even [Los Angeles High School](/Los_Angeles_High_School), highlighting the fluid and less formally structured nature of interscholastic and intercollegiate competition in that nascent era.

The Southern California Intercollegiate Athletic Conference formally came into existence in 1915, founded by five visionary institutions with the explicit aim of promoting and upholding the ideals of amateurism in collegiate athletics. This commitment to amateur status, particularly within [NCAA Division III](/NCAA_Division_III), remains a defining characteristic, ostensibly prioritizing educational development over purely athletic pursuits. The five founding members, all of whom maintain ties to the conference today, were [Throop College of Technology](/California_Institute_of_Technology) (the precursor to the renowned [California Institute of Technology](/California_Institute_of_Technology)), [Occidental College](/Occidental_College), [Pomona College](/Pomona_College), the [University of Redlands](/University_of_Redlands), and [Whittier College](/Whittier_College). While all five are still affiliated, only [Occidental](/Occidental_College) and [Redlands](/University_of_Redlands) have enjoyed an unbroken, continuous membership since the conference's inception—a testament to their enduring commitment, or perhaps simply a lack of compelling reasons to depart. It's an amusing historical footnote that the acronym "SCIAC" itself was in circulation prior to the conference's founding, used between 1913 and 1914 by the Southern California Interscholastic Athletic Council, an organization that ultimately transitioned into the [CIF Southern Section](/CIF_Southern_Section). This earlier usage indicates a regional tradition of athletic councils, laying groundwork for what was to come. [1]

A significant moment in the conference's modern history occurred on May 12, 2011, when the SCIAC officially welcomed [Chapman University](/Chapman_University) as its ninth full member. This expansion, which saw Chapman begin competition in the 2011–12 academic year, marked the first growth in conference membership since [California Lutheran University](/California_Lutheran_University) joined in 1991. Such expansions are often driven by a desire for increased competition, geographical balance, or simply the pragmatic need to maintain a viable number of participating institutions. Interestingly, a historical thread running through many of the SCIAC's member colleges is their past affiliation with various Christian denominations, including the [Quakers](/Quakers) and the [Presbyterians](/Presbyterians). Today, however, only [California Lutheran University](/California_Lutheran_University) maintains an active, official affiliation with a church, reflecting a broader trend of secularization among academic institutions, or perhaps a strategic decision to appeal to a wider demographic.

The narrative of the SCIAC also includes the stories of institutions that have moved on to different, often larger, stages. Three former members, once integral to the conference, now compete in the more competitive and high-profile realm of [NCAA Division I](/NCAA_Division_I) athletics. These include the [University of California, Los Angeles](/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles) (UCLA), [San Diego State University](/San_Diego_State_University), and the [University of California, Santa Barbara](/University_of_California,_Santa_Barbara). Their departures highlight the common trajectory for institutions with burgeoning athletic ambitions, often leaving behind the smaller, academically focused [Division III](/NCAA_Division_III) environment for the perceived prestige and resources of [Division I](/NCAA_Division_I).

#### Chronological timeline

The history of the SCIAC is a dynamic chronicle of evolving alliances, temporary departures, and strategic re-engagements, reflecting the ever-shifting landscape of collegiate sports.

*   **1915** – The [Southern California Intercollegiate Athletic Conference](/Southern_California_Intercollegiate_Athletic_Conference) (SCIAC) was officially inaugurated. Its foundational members, committing to the spirit of amateur athletics, included [Occidental College](/Occidental_College), [Pomona College](/Pomona_College), the [University of Redlands](/University_of_Redlands), [Throop College of Technology](/California_Institute_of_Technology) (the institution that would eventually become [California Institute of Technology](/California_Institute_of_Technology)), and [Whittier College](/Whittier_College). Their inaugural academic year of competition commenced in 1915–16.
*   **1920** – The [Southern Branch of the University of California](/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles), which would later be globally recognized as the [University of California at Los Angeles](/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles) (UCLA), joined the SCIAC for the 1920–21 academic year, marking a brief affiliation with a future collegiate powerhouse.
*   **1926** – Expansion continued with the addition of [La Verne College](/University_of_La_Verne) (now known as the [University of La Verne](/University_of_La_Verne)) and [San Diego State Teachers College](/San_Diego_State_University) (which would evolve into [San Diego State University](/San_Diego_State_University)). Both institutions began their participation in the 1926–27 academic year.
*   **1927** – [UCLA](/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles), having quickly ascended beyond the conference's scope, departed the SCIAC following the 1926–27 academic year.
*   **1931** – [Santa Barbara State College](/University_of_California,_Santa_Barbara) (the future [University of California at Santa Barbara](/University_of_California,_Santa_Barbara)) was welcomed into the SCIAC, commencing its membership in the 1931–32 academic year.
*   **1934** – A double departure saw both [Caltech](/California_Institute_of_Technology) and [Pomona College](/Pomona_College) withdraw from the SCIAC after the 1933–34 academic year. Reasons for this synchronized exit remain a matter of historical record.
*   **1938**: This year was marked by a flurry of membership changes.
    *   [La Verne](/University_of_La_Verne) and [UC Santa Barbara](/University_of_California,_Santa_Barbara) concluded their respective tenures with the SCIAC after the 1937–38 academic year.
    *   In a seemingly contradictory move, both [Caltech](/California_Institute_of_Technology) and [Pomona](/Pomona_College) rejoined the SCIAC, their return effective for the 1938–39 academic year. It seems some bonds, however briefly severed, are destined to reform.
*   **1939** – [San Diego State](/San_Diego_State_University) definitively left the SCIAC after the 1938–39 academic year, charting its course towards larger athletic divisions.
*   **1943** – [Whittier College](/Whittier_College) experienced a temporary cessation of membership, departing the SCIAC after the 1942–43 academic year.
*   **1946** – [Whittier College](/Whittier_College) swiftly returned to the fold, rejoining the SCIAC for the 1946–47 academic year.
*   **1947** – [Claremont Men's College](/Claremont_McKenna_College) (which would later be known as [Claremont McKenna College](/Claremont_McKenna_College)) was added to the conference, beginning its participation in the 1947–48 academic year.
*   **1950** – [Chapman College](/Chapman_University) (now [Chapman University](/Chapman_University)) joined the SCIAC for the 1950–51 academic year.
*   **1952** – [Chapman](/Chapman_University)'s initial stint in the SCIAC was brief, as it departed after the 1951–52 academic year.
*   **1958** – A new model of athletic collaboration emerged as [Claremont](/Claremont_McKenna_College) combined its athletic programs with [Harvey Mudd College](/Harvey_Mudd_College) to form the 'Claremont–Mudd' athletic entity, effective for the 1958–59 academic year.
*   **1971** – This year marked a significant restructuring: [Pomona](/Pomona_College) and [Pitzer College](/Pitzer_College) joined forces for athletics, creating 'Pomona–Pitzer', while [La Verne](/University_of_La_Verne) made its return to the SCIAC. Both changes were implemented for the 1971–72 academic year.
*   **1976** – The combined 'Claremont–Mudd' athletic program further expanded its scope by integrating [Scripps College](/Scripps_College), thereby becoming the comprehensive 'Claremont–Mudd–Scripps' athletic collective, effective from the 1976–77 academic year.
*   **1991** – [California Lutheran University](/California_Lutheran_University) was welcomed as the newest member of the SCIAC, beginning its participation in the 1991–92 academic year.
*   **2011** – After a considerable absence, [Chapman](/Chapman_University) rejoined the SCIAC, with its renewed membership commencing in the 2011–12 academic year.
*   **2020** – [Occidental College](/Occidental_College) made the difficult decision to discontinue its [football](/American_football) program, a change implemented before the start of the 2020 fall season (2020–21 academic year).
*   **2023** – [Whittier College](/Whittier_College) also ceased its [football](/American_football) program, doing so after the conclusion of the 2022 fall season (2022–23 academic year), reflecting a trend among some [Division III](/NCAA_Division_III) institutions.
*   **2024** – [Azusa Pacific University](/Azusa_Pacific_University) announced a noteworthy transition, moving from [NCAA Division II](/NCAA_Division_II) and the [Pacific West Conference](/Pacific_West_Conference) to join the SCIAC. This strategic shift is timed to coincide with the re-establishment of its [football](/American_football) program for the 2026 fall season, effective for the 2026–27 academic year.

### Member schools

#### Current member schools

The SCIAC currently comprises nine full members, all of which are distinguished [private](/Private_university) academic institutions. [3] Their diverse histories, affiliations, and athletic profiles contribute to the rich tapestry of the conference.

